Polish Stocks: Netia, New World Resources, NG2, Warsaw Exchange

-- B y   P a w e l   K o z l o w s k i
-- 
2011-06-02T15:57:15Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-02/polish-stocks-netia-new-world-resources-ng2-warsaw-exchange.html
Poland ’s WIG20 Index fell 5.56, or
0.2 percent, to 2,896.05.  The following are among the most active stocks on the
Warsaw Stock Exchange today. Stock symbols follow company names.  Netia SA (NET)   gained 0.11 zloty, or 1.9 percent, to 5.8
zloty, the highest close in more than five years. Shareholders
of Poland’s second-largest fixed-line phone company approved a
plan to buy back as much as 350 million zloty ($128 million) of
shares over the next two years, the PAP newswire reported.  NG2 SA (CCC)  , Poland’s biggest publicly traded shoe
retailer, jumped 2.4 zloty, or 4.3 percent, to 58.5 zloty,
rising for the first time this week. Sales rose 44 percent to
103.1 million zloty in May from a year earlier.  New World Resources Plc (NWR PW) declined for a third day
in Warsaw trading, sliding 2.36 zloty, or 5.5 percent, to 40.6
zloty after the  Czech Republic ’s biggest coking-coal producer
said its majority shareholder will sell as much as a 6.1 percent
stake in the company.  Warsaw Stock Exchange (GPW)   declined for a second day,
losing 0.9 zloty, or 1.7 percent, to 52.9 zloty. Total stock
turnover on its main market fell 11 percent to 23.5 billion
zloty in May from a year earlier, the company said in an e-
mailed statement today.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Pawel Kozlowski in Warsaw 
